    "narrative": "For the May 1st slate, **Gunnar Henderson** stands as our premier anchor with a 74.07 rating. Leading off against Will Warren, he benefits from a massive 14% dynamic platoon advantage, and while Warren is a decent arm, the combination of the #1 lineup spot and Henderson\u2019s raw output makes him our engine today. Similarly, **Vladimir Guerrero Jr.** (72.39) is a high-conviction start; despite facing a righty in Simeon Woods Richardson, his elite xwOBA of .389 and the favorable 4.87 xERA matchup make him a locked-in power threat. We are also capitalizing on the soft matchup against Christian Scott; both **Nolan Schanuel** and **Josh Lowe** see their scores inflated by the SP\u2019s 15.44 xERA, turning what might be fringe plays into high-ceiling opportunities. **Josh Lowe** in particular is a priority, as he carries the speed profile we weigh heavily in this 5x5 format.\n\nThe most difficult decision on the bench involves **Marcell Ozuna**, who sits at a 58.45 rating. Despite a favorable wind-out condition adding 5% to his base, he fell just short of the cutoff because we prioritized the higher floor provided by **Dominic Smith**'s park factor and the specific matchup against the vulnerable Jose Quintana. Elsewhere, **Heliot Ramos** remains a start (59.04) despite a tougher assignment against Shane McClanahan, largely because his 100% stolen base opportunity rate against the pitcher's delivery pace aligns with our strategic focus on SB scarcity. \n\nA note of caution: all assignments today are contingent on \"Lineup Pending\" status. While we have modeled based on expected spots, a late-hour shuffle could impact the 8-10% order-based bonuses currently baked into the projections for **Drake Baldwin** and **Miguel Vargas**. We are monitoring the weather closely, but the primary risk remains the reliance on projected lineup positions. If **Jackson Merrill** or **Josh Jung** appear in more favorable spots than initially anticipated, we will evaluate if a late-afternoon swap is necessary to maintain our categorical efficiency.",
